# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sap-erp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] ABAP is one of the many application-specific fourth-generation languages (4GLs) first developed in the 1980s.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] It was originally the report language for SAP R/2, a platform that enabled large corporations to build mainframe business applications for materials management and financial and management accounting.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] ABAP was originally an acronym for ***A**llgemeiner **B**erichts-**A**ufbereitungs-**P**rozessor* ("generic report preparation processor" in German), but was later rebranded as ***A**dvanced **B**usiness **A**pplication **P**rogramming*.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] ABAP was one of the first languages to include the concept of *Logical Databases* (LDBs), which provides a high level of abstraction from the basic database level(s), which supports every platform, language and units.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The ABAP language was originally used by developers to develop the SAP R/3 platform.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] It was also intended to be used by SAP customers to enhance SAP applications – customers can develop custom reports and interfaces with ABAP programming.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The language was geared towards more technical customers with programming experience.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] ABAP remains as the language for creating programs for the client–server R/3 system, which SAP first released in 1992.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] As computer hardware evolved through the 1990s, more and more of SAP's applications and systems were written in ABAP.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] By 2001, all but the most basic functions were written in ABAP.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] In 1999, SAP released an object-oriented extension to ABAP called ABAP Objects, along with R/3 release 4.6.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] SAP's current development platform NetWeaver supports both ABAP and Java.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] ABAP has an abstraction between the business applications, the operating system and database.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] This ensures that applications do not depend directly upon a specific server or database platform and can easily be ported from one platform to another.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] SAP Netweaver currently runs on UNIX (AIX, HP-UX, Solaris, Linux), Microsoft Windows, i5/OS on IBM System i (formerly iSeries, AS/400), and z/OS on IBM System z (formerly zSeries, S/390).
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Supported databases are HANA, SAP ASE (formerly Sybase), IBM Db2, Informix, MaxDB, Oracle, and Microsoft SQL Server (support for Informix was discontinued in SAP Basis release 7.00).
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] All ABAP programs reside inside the SAP database.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] They are not stored in separate external files like Java or C++ programs.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] In the database all ABAP code exists in two forms: source code, which can be viewed and edited with the ABAP Workbench tools; and generated code, a binary representation somewhat comparable with Java bytecode.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] ABAP programs execute under the control of the runtime system, which is part of the SAP kernel.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The runtime system is responsible for processing ABAP statements, controlling the flow logic of screens and responding to events (such as a user clicking on a screen button); in this respect it can be seen as a Virtual Machine comparable with the Java VM.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] A key component of the ABAP runtime system is the Database Interface, which turns database-independent ABAP statements ("Open SQL") into statements understood by the underlying DBMS ("Native SQL").
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The database interface handles all the communication with the relational database on behalf of ABAP programs; It also contains extra features such as buffering of tables and frequently accessed data in the local memory of the application server.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] All SAP data exists and all SAP software runs in the context of a *SAP system*.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] A system consists of a central relational database and one or more application servers ("instances") accessing the data and programs in this database.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] A SAP system contains at least one instance but may contain more, mostly for reasons of sizing and performance.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] In a system with multiple instances, load balancing mechanisms ensure that the load is spread evenly over the available application servers.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Installations of the Web Application Server (*landscapes*) typically consist of three systems: one for development; one for testing and quality assurance; and one for production.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The landscape may contain more systems (e.g., separate systems for unit testing and pre-production testing) or it may contain fewer (e.g., only development and production, without separate QA); nevertheless three is the most common configuration.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] ABAP programs are created and undergo first testing in the development system.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Afterwards they are distributed to the other systems in the landscape.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] These actions take place under control of the Change and Transport System (CTS), which is responsible for concurrency control (e.g., preventing two developers from changing the same code at the same time), version management, and deployment of programs on the QA and production systems.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The Web Application Server consists of three layers: the database layer; the application layer; and the presentation layer.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] These layers may run on the same or on different physical machines.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The *database layer* contains the relational database and the database software.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The 'application layer' knowledge contains the instance or instances of the system.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] All application processes, including the business transactions and the ABAP development, run on the application layer.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The *presentation layer* handles the interaction with users of the system.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Online access to ABAP application servers can go via a proprietary graphical interface, which is called "SAP GUI", or via a Web browser.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] ABAP software is deployed in software components.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] A transaction in SAP terminology is the execution of a program.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The normal way of executing ABAP code in the SAP system is by entering a transaction code (for instance, VA01 is the transaction code for "Create Sales Order").
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The common transaction codes (T-codes) used by ABAP developer are SE38, SE09, SE10, SE24, SE11, SE16N, SE80, SE37, ST22 etc.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Transactions can be called via system-defined or user-specific, role-based menus.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] They can also be started by entering the transaction code directly into a command field, which is present in every SAP screen.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Transactions can also be invoked programmatically by means of the ABAP statements `CALL TRANSACTION` and `LEAVE TO TRANSACTION.` The general notion of a transaction is called a Logical Unit of Work (LUW) in SAP terminology.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] As in other programming languages, an ABAP program is either an executable unit or a library, which provides reusable code to other programs and is not independently executable.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Reports follow a relatively simple programming model whereby a user optionally enters a set of parameters (e.g., a selection over a subSET of data) and the program then uses the input parameters to produce a report in the form of an interactive list.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The term "report" can be somewhat misleading in that reports can also be designed to *modify* data; the reason why these programs are called reports is the "list-oriented" nature of the output they produce.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Module pools define more complex patterns of user interaction using a collection of screens.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The term “screen” refers to the actual, physical image that the user sees.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Each screen also has a "flow logic", which refers to the ABAP code implicitly invoked by the screens, which is divided into a "PBO" (Process Before Output) and "PAI" (Process After Input) section.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] In SAP documentation the term “dynpro” (dynamic program) refers to the combination of the screen and its flow logic.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] ABAP programs are composed of individual sentences (statements).
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The first word in a statement is called an ABAP keyword.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Words must always be separated by at least one space.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] With keywords, additions and operands, the ABAP runtime system does not differentiate between upper and lowercase.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] You can have several statements in a single line (though this is not recommended).
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Lines that begin with asterisk * in the first column are recognized as comment lines by the ABAP runtime system and are ignored.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Double quotations marks (") indicate that the remainder of a line is a comment.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] There are two possible ways to develop in ABAP.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The availability depends on the release of the ABAP system.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The **ABAP Workbench** is part of the ABAP system and is accessed via SAP GUI.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] It contains different tools for editing programs.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The *Object Navigator* (transaction SE80) provides a single integrated interface into these various tools.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The **ABAP Development Tools** (**ADT**), formally known as "ABAP in Eclipse", is a set of plugins for the Eclipse IDE to develop ABAP objects.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] In this scenario, the ABAP developer installs the required tools on their computer and works locally, whereas a continuous synchronization with the backend is performed.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The ABAP Dictionary contains all metadata about the data in the SAP system.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] It is closely linked with the ABAP Workbench in that any reference to data (e.g., a table, a view, or a data type) will be obtained from the dictionary.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Developers use the ABAP Dictionary transactions (directly or through the SE80 Object Navigator inside the ABAP Workbench) to display and maintain this metadata.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] When a dictionary object is changed, a program that references the changed object will automatically reference the new version the next time the program runs.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Because ABAP is interpreted, it is not necessary to recompile programs that reference changed dictionary objects.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] This brief description of the ABAP syntax begins with the ubiquitous "Hello".
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] This example contains two statements: `REPORT` and `WRITE`.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The program displays a list on the screen.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] In this case, the list consists of the single line "Hello, World!".
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The `REPORT` statement indicates that this program is a report.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] This program could be a module pool after replacing the `REPORT` statement with `PROGRAM`.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Consecutive statements with an identical first (leftmost) part can be combined into a "chained" statement using the chain operator `:`.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The common part of the statements is written to the left of the colon, the differing parts are written to the right of the colon and separated by commas.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The colon operator is attached directly to the preceding token, without a space (the same applies to the commas in the token list on, as can be seen in the examples below).
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Chaining is often used in `WRITE` statements.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] In a chain statement, the first part (before the colon) is not limited to the statement name alone.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The entire common part of the consecutive statements can be placed before the colon.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] assigns to variable x the substring of the variable a, starting from b with the length defined by the variable c.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] assigns to variable x the sum of the variable a and the result of the call to method b with the parameter c.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] In contrast with languages like C/C++ or Java, which define a limited set of language-specific statements and provide most functionality via libraries, ABAP contains an extensive amount of built-in statements.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] These statements traditionally used sentence-like structures and avoided symbols, making ABAP programs relatively verbose.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] However, in more recent versions of the ABAP language, a terser style is possible.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] ABAP provides a set of built-in data types.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] In addition, every structure, table, view or data element defined in the ABAP Dictionary can be used to type a variable.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Also, object classes and interfaces can be used as types.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Date variables or constants (type D) contain the number of days since January 1, 1 AD.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Time variables or constants (type T) contain the number of seconds since midnight.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] A special characteristic of both types is that they can be accessed both as integers and as character strings (with internal format "YYYYMMDD" for dates and "hhmmss" for times), which can be used for date and time handling.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] All ABAP variables have to be explicitly declared in order to be used.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] They can be declared either with individual statements and explicit typing or, since ABAP 7.40, inline with inferred typing.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Normally all declarations are placed at the top of the code module (program, subroutine, function) before the first executable statement; this placement is a convention and not an enforced syntax rule.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Notice the use of the colon to chain together consecutive DATA statements.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] For this type of declaration it must be possible to infer the type statically, e.g. by method signature or database table structure.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The ABAP language supports object-oriented programming, through a feature known as "ABAP Objects".
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] This helps to simplify applications and make them more controllable.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] ABAP Objects is fully compatible with the existing language, so one can use existing statements and modularization units in programs that use ABAP Objects, and can also use ABAP Objects in existing ABAP programs.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Syntax checking is stronger in ABAP Objects programs, and some syntactical forms (usually older ones) of certain statements are not permitted.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Objects form a capsule which combines the character to the respective behavior.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Objects should enable programmers to map a real problem and its proposed software solution on a one-to-one basis.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Typical objects in a business environment are, for example, ‘Customer’, ‘Order’, or ‘Invoice’.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] From Release 3.1 onwards, the Business Object Repository (BOR) of SAP Web Application Server ABAP has contained examples of such objects.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The BOR object model will be integrated into ABAP Objects in the next Release by migrating the BOR object types to the ABAP class library.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] A comprehensive introduction to object orientation as a whole would go far beyond the limits of this introduction to ABAP Objects.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] This documentation introduces a selection of terms that are used universally in object orientation and also occur in ABAP Objects.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] In subsequent sections, it goes on to discuss in more detail how these terms are used in ABAP Objects.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The end of this section contains a list of further reading, with a selection of titles about object orientation.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The ABAP Core Data Services (ABAP CDS) are the implementation of the general CDS concept for AS ABAP.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] ABAP CDS makes it possible to define semantic data models on the central database of the application server.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] On AS ABAP, these models can be defined independently of the database system.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The entities of these models provide enhanced access functions when compared with existing database tables and views defined in ABAP Dictionary, making it possible to optimize Open SQL-based applications.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] This is particularly clear when an AS ABAP uses a SAP HANA database, since its in-memory characteristics can be implemented in an optimum manner.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The data models are defined using the data definition language (DDL) and data control language (DCL) provided in the ABAP CDS in the ABAP CDS syntax.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The objects defined using these languages are integrated into ABAP Dictionary and managed here too.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] CDS source code can only be programmed in the Eclipse-based ABAP Development Tools (ADT).
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The Data Definition Language (DDL) and the Data Control Language (DCL) use different editors.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Internal tables are an important feature of the ABAP language.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] An internal table is defined similarly to a vector of *struct*s in C++ or a vector of objects in Java.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The main difference with these languages is that ABAP provides a collection of statements to easily access and manipulate the contents of internal tables.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Note that ABAP does not support arrays; the only way to define a multi-element data object is to use an internal table.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Internal tables are a way to store variable data sets of a fixed structure in the working memory of ABAP, and provides the functionality of dynamic arrays.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The data is stored on a row-by-row basis, where each row has the same structure.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Internal tables are preferably used to store and format the content of database tables from within a program.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] Furthermore, internal tables in connection with structures are an important means of defining complex data structures in an ABAP program.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p01] The following example defines an internal table with two fields with the format of database table VBRK.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p02] The following list only gives a rough overview about some important milestones in the history of the language ABAP.
[src:sap-erp/abap-p02] For more details, see ABAP – Release-Specific Changes.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The finance module in particular is essential to a suite of applications meeting the definition of an ERP system.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The finance module provides the **system of record** for the organisation; recording the commercial impact of the business operations in the General Ledger.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP provides an integrated and continuously updated view of core business processes, typically using a shared database managed by a database management system.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems track business resources—cash, raw materials, production capacity—and the status of business commitments: orders, purchase orders, and payroll.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The applications that make up the system share data across various departments (manufacturing, purchasing, sales, accounting, etc.) that provide the data.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP facilitates information flow between all business functions and manages connections to outside stakeholders.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Estimates of the size of the global ERP market range between USD $78 and $81 billion in 2026 .
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Though early ERP systems focused on large enterprises, smaller enterprises increasingly use ERP systems.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The ERP system integrates varied organizational systems and facilitates error-free transactions and production, thereby enhancing the organization's efficiency.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] However, developing an ERP system differs from traditional system development.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems run on a variety of computer hardware and network configurations, typically using a database as an information repository.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Business and technology research and advisory firm Gartner is credited for first using the acronym ERP in the 1990s.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The term captured a functional extension of two manufacturing-based concepts, material requirements planning (MRP) and manufacturing resource planning (MRP II).
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Without replacing these terms, ERP came to represent a larger whole that reflected the evolution of application integration beyond manufacturing.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Not all ERP packages are developed from a manufacturing core; ERP vendors variously began assembling their packages with finance-and-accounting, maintenance, and human-resource components.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] By the mid-1990s ERP systems addressed all core enterprise functions.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Governments and non–profit organizations also began to use ERP systems.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] An "ERP system selection methodology" is a formal process for selecting an enterprise resource planning (ERP) system.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Existing methodologies include: Kuiper's funnel method, Dobrin's three-dimensional (3D) web-based decision support tool, and the Clarkston Potomac methodology.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems experienced rapid growth in the 1990s.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Because of the year 2000 problem many companies took the opportunity to replace their old systems with ERP.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems initially focused on automating back office functions that did not directly affect customers and the public.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Front office functions, such as customer relationship management (CRM), dealt directly with customers, or e-business systems such as e-commerce and e-government—or supplier relationship management (SRM) became integrated later, when the internet simplified communicating with external parties.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] "ERP II" was coined in 2000 in an article by Gartner Publications entitled *ERP Is Dead—Long Live ERP II*.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] It describes web–based software that provides real–time access to ERP systems to employees and partners (such as suppliers and customers).
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The ERP II role expands traditional ERP resource optimization and transaction processing.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Rather than just manage buying, selling, etc.—ERP II leverages information in the resources under its management to help the enterprise collaborate with other enterprises.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP II is more flexible than the first generation ERP.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Rather than confine ERP system capabilities within the organization, it goes beyond the corporate walls to interact with other systems.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Enterprise application suite is an alternate name for such systems.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP II systems are typically used to enable collaborative initiatives such as supply chain management (SCM), customer relationship management (CRM) and business intelligence (BI) among business partner organizations through the use of various electronic business technologies.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The large proportion of companies are pursuing a strong managerial targets in ERP system instead of acquire an ERP company.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Developers now make more effort to integrate mobile devices with the ERP system.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP vendors are extending ERP to these devices, along with other business applications, so that businesses don't have to rely on third-party applications.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] As an example, the e-commerce platform Shopify was able to make ERP tools from Microsoft and Oracle available on its app in October 2021.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Technical stakes of modern ERP concern integration—hardware, applications, networking, supply chains.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP now covers more functions and roles—including decision making, stakeholders' relationships, standardization, transparency, globalization, etc.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] From 1999 the ERP industry underwent a paradigm shift from the existing on-premise model (i.e. separate installations of the ERP system on the client's or third-party servers) to cloud (i.e. the ERP system is served to the user via a web browser with all of it's components hosted in data centres).
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] This followed the launch of early pure cloud ERP systems such as NetLedger.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] This shift required massive technology and business model changes from the ERP vendors.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] An ERP system covers the following common functional areas.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Government resource planning (GRP) is the equivalent of an ERP for the public sector and an integrated office automation system for government bodies.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The software structure, modularization, core algorithms and main interfaces do not differ from other ERPs, and ERP software suppliers manage to adapt their systems to government agencies.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Most ERP systems incorporate best practices.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] This means the software reflects the vendor's interpretation of the most effective way to perform each business process.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Systems vary in how conveniently the customer can modify these practices.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Use of best practices eases compliance with requirements such as International Financial Reporting Standards, Sarbanes–Oxley, or Basel II.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] They can also help comply with de facto industry standards, such as electronic funds transfer.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] This is because the procedure can be readily codified within the ERP software and replicated with confidence across multiple businesses that share that business requirement.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems connect to real–time data and transaction data in a variety of ways.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] These systems are typically configured by systems integrators, who bring unique knowledge on process, equipment, and vendor solutions.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP's scope usually implies significant changes to staff work processes and practices.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Generally, three types of services are available to help implement such changes: consulting, customization, and support.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Implementation time depends on business size, number of modules, customization, the scope of process changes, and the readiness of the customer to take ownership for the project.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Modular ERP systems can be implemented in stages.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The typical project for a large enterprise takes about 14 months and requires around 150 consultants.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Small projects can require months; multinational and other large implementations can take years.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Customization can substantially increase implementation times.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Besides that, information processing influences various business functions e.g. some large corporations like Walmart use a just in time inventory system.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] This reduces inventory storage and increases delivery efficiency, and requires up-to-date data.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Before 2014, Walmart used a system called Inforem developed by IBM to manage replenishment.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The outcome of the implementation process will be significantly impacted by the skills and experience of the implementing team combined with a tried and tested implementation methodology that provides guardrails to drive the project to success.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP implementations are a specific sub-type of project however there is no industry-specified standard methodology.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Implementation methodologies are created by the ERP vendors or the specialist ERP consulting firms, generally known as Value Added Resellers (VARs), who carry out the implementations.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Each implementer's methodology can be assessed as to how well it meets the principles and practices outlined in the guides of the project management peak industry bodies such as Project Management Institute.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Implementing ERP typically requires changes in existing business processes.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Poor understanding of needed process changes prior to starting implementation is a main reason for project failure.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The difficulties could be related to the system, business process, infrastructure, training, or lack of motivation.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] It is therefore crucial that organizations thoroughly analyze processes before they deploy an ERP software.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Analysis can identify opportunities for process modernization.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] It also enables an assessment of the alignment of current processes with those provided by the ERP system.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP implementation is considerably more difficult (and politically charged) in decentralized organizations, because they often have different processes, business rules, data semantics, authorization hierarchies, and decision centers.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] This may require migrating some business units before others, delaying implementation to work through the necessary changes for each unit, possibly reducing integration (e.g., linking via master data management) or customizing the system to meet specific needs.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] A potential disadvantage is that adopting "standard" processes can lead to a loss of competitive advantage.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] While this has happened, losses in one area are often offset by gains in other areas, increasing overall competitive advantage.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Configuring an ERP system is largely a matter of balancing the way the organization wants the system to work, and the way the system is designed to work out of the box.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems typically include many configurable settings that in effect modify system operations.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] For example, in the ServiceNow platform, business rules can be written requiring the signature of a business owner within 2 weeks of a newly completed risk assessment.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The tool can be configured to automatically email notifications to the business owner, and transition the risk assessment to various stages in the process depending on the owner's responses or lack thereof.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Two-tier ERP software and hardware lets companies run the equivalent of two ERP systems at once: one at the corporate level and one at the division or subsidiary level.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] For example, a manufacturing company could use an ERP system to manage across the organization using independent global or regional distribution, production or sales centers, and service providers to support the main company's customers.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Each independent center (or) subsidiary may have its own business operations cycles, workflows, and business processes.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Given the realities of globalization, enterprises continuously evaluate how to optimize their regional, divisional, and product or manufacturing strategies to support strategic goals and reduce time-to-market while increasing profitability and delivering value.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] With two-tier ERP, the regional distribution, production, or sales centers and service providers continue operating under their own business model—separate from the main company, using their own ERP systems.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Since these smaller companies' processes and workflows are not tied to main company's processes and workflows, they can respond to local business requirements in multiple locations.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] An alternative to a two-tier approach is to use as an ERP system which allows for multiple workflows to be configured for the same function.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] This allows each operation or division to have its own workflow, say for order entry.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] This avoids the need to integrate two ERP systems as all divisions and operations are running within the same ERP system.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems are theoretically based on industry best practices, and their makers intend that organizations deploy them "as is".
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP vendors do offer customers configuration options that let organizations incorporate their own business rules, but gaps in features often remain even after configuration is complete.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP customers have several options to reconcile feature gaps, each with their own pros/cons.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Technical solutions include rewriting part of the delivered software, writing a homegrown module to work within the ERP system, or interfacing to an external system.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] These three options constitute varying degrees of system customization—with the first being the most invasive and costly to maintain.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Alternatively, there are non-technical options such as changing business practices or organizational policies to better match the delivered ERP feature set.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] ERP systems can be extended with third-party software, often via vendor-supplied interfaces.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Data migration is the process of moving, copying, and restructuring data from an existing system to an enterprise resource planning (ERP) system.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] It is a critical component of a successful implementation and requires thorough planning.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] However, because migration typically occurs near the end of the implementation process, it often receives inadequate attention.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Often, data migration is incomplete because some of the data in the existing system is either incompatible or not needed in the new system.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] As such, the existing system may need to be kept as an archived database to refer back to once the new ERP system is in place.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The most fundamental advantage of ERP is that the integration of a myriad of business processes saves time and expense.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Management can make decisions faster and with fewer errors.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Data becomes visible across the organization.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Research published in 2011 based on a survey of 225 manufacturers, retailers and distributors found "high" rates of interest and adoption of ERP systems and that very few businesses were "completely untouched" by the concept of an ERP system.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] 27% of the companies survey had a fully operational system, 12% were at that time rolling out a system and 26% had an existing ERP system which they were extending or upgrading.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The term "postmodern ERP" was coined by Gartner in 2013, when it first appeared in the paper series "Predicts 2014".
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The basic idea is that there should still be a core ERP solution that would cover most important business functions, while other functions will be covered by specialist software solutions that merely extend the core ERP.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] This concept is similar to the "best-of-breed" approach to software execution, but it shouldn't be confused with it.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] While in both cases, applications that make up the whole are relatively loosely connected and quite easily interchangeable, in the case of the latter there is no ERP solution whatsoever.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] Instead, every business function is covered by a separate software solution.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] There is, however, no golden rule as to what business functions should be part of the core ERP, and what should be covered by supplementary solutions.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] According to Gartner, every company must define their own postmodern ERP strategy, based on company's internal and external needs, operations and processes.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] For example, a company may define that the core ERP solution should cover those business processes that must stay behind the firewall, and therefore, choose to leave their core ERP on-premises.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] At the same time, another company may adopt a hybrid ERP approach, hosting the core ERP solution in the cloud while moving only a few ERP modules as supplementary solutions to on-premises.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The main benefits that companies will gain from implementing postmodern ERP strategy are speed and flexibility when reacting to unexpected changes in business processes or on the organizational level.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] With the majority of applications having a relatively loose connection, it is fairly easy to replace or upgrade them whenever necessary.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] In addition to that, following the examples above, companies can select and combine cloud-based and on-premises solutions that are most suited for their ERP needs.
[src:sap-erp/enterprise-resource-planning] The downside of postmodern ERP is that it will most likely lead to an increased number of software vendors that companies will have to manage, as well as pose additional integration challenges for the central IT.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] An ERP was built based on the former SAP R/3 software.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] SAP R/3, which was officially launched on 6 July 1992, consisted of various applications on top of SAP Basis, SAP's set of middleware programs and tools.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] All applications were built on top of the SAP Web Application Server.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] Extension sets were used to deliver new features and keep the core as stable as possible.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] The Web Application Server contained all the capabilities of SAP Basis.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] An architecture change took place with the introduction of my SAP ERP in 2004.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] R/3 Enterprise was replaced with the introduction of ERP Central Component (SAP ECC).
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] The SAP Business Warehouse, SAP Strategic Enterprise Management and Internet Transaction Server were also merged into SAP ECC, allowing users to run them under one instance.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] The SAP Web Application Server was wrapped into SAP NetWeaver, which was introduced in 2003.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] Architectural changes were also made to support an enterprise service architecture to transition customers to a service-oriented architecture.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] The latest version, SAP ERP 6.0, was released in 2006.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] SAP ERP 6.0 has since then been updated through SAP enhancement packs, the most recent: SAP enhancement package 8 for SAP ERP 6.0 was released in 2016.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] As of SAP ERP 6.0 EhP8, SAP has shifted its focus to SAP S/4HANA, which provides a flexible deployment method and, SAP Activate methodology that goes through structured phases of SAP ERP Implementation to leverage real-time operations, Fiori-driven user experience (UX), and continuous innovation.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] It is estimated that "for a Fortune 500 company, software, hardware, and consulting costs can easily exceed $100 million (around $50 million to $500 million).
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] Large companies can also spend $50 million to $100 million on upgrades.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] Full implementation of all modules can take years", which also adds to the end price.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] Independent studies have shown that deployment and maintenance costs of a SAP solution can vary depending on the organization.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] For example, some point out that because of the rigid model imposed by SAP tools, a lot of customization code to adapt to the business process may have to be developed and maintained.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] Some others pointed out that a return on investment could only be obtained when there was both a sufficient number of users and sufficient frequency of use.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] SAP Transport Management System (STMS) is a tool within SAP ERP systems to manage software updates, termed *transports*, on one or more connected SAP systems.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] The tool can be accessed from transaction code STMS.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] This should not be confused with SAP Transportation Management, a stand-alone module for facilitating logistics and supply chain management in the transportation of goods and materials.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] The latest version (SAP ERP 6.0) was made available in 2006.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] Since then, additional functionality for SAP ERP 6.0 has been delivered through SAP Enhancement Packages (EhP).
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] These Enhancement Packages allow SAP ERP customers to manage and deploy new software functionality.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] Enhancement Packages are optional; customers choose which new capabilities to implement.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] SAP EhPs do not require a classic system upgrade.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] The technical installation of business functions does not change the system behavior.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] The installation of new functionalities is decoupled from its activation and companies can choose which business functions they want to activate.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] This means that even after installing a new business function, there is no change to existing functionality before activation.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] Activating a business function for one process will have no effect on users working with other functionalities.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] Reaching its final stage, SAP ECC 6.0 concludes its evolution with Enhancement Package 8 (EHP 8.0).
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] EhP8 served as a foundation to transition to SAP's new business suite: SAP S/4HANA.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] In 2025, SAP introduced a new phase in the evolution of its ERP portfolio with the launch of SAP Cloud ERP, positioned as the successor to both legacy SAP ERP and SAP Business Suite.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] The platform reflects SAP’s move to a cloud-first, AI-enabled model that integrates SAP Business Data Cloud, SAP Business AI, and SAP Build, with an emphasis on maintaining a clean-core architecture that simplifies upgrades and extensions.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] A central part of this shift is the integration of Joule, SAP’s AI copilot, along with intelligent applications in areas such as Finance, Supply Chain Management, and Human Capital Management (HCM).
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] These capabilities extend traditional ERP functions with real-time analytics, guided automation, and AI-driven decision support.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] Independent sources highlight how this modular approach is intended to help organizations modernize without the heavy customizations that defined earlier ERP generations.
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] A practical overview of how these cloud capabilities connect with SAP BTP, AI Core, Joule, Finance, SCM, and HCM. .
[src:sap-erp/sap-erp] To support customers who are still running on-premises ERP or SAP Business Suite systems, SAP also introduced a new ERP private edition, transition option, allowing organizations to extend their use of existing systems while planning migrations to SAP S/4HANA or Cloud ERP between 2031 and 2033.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] As of 2005 SAP SE did not commercialize its own proprietary database technology.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Many customers ran SAP applications on non-SAP databases from vendors such as Oracle Corporation and Software AG.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The first major demonstration of the platform was in 2011: teams from SAP SE, the Hasso Plattner Institute and Stanford University demonstrated an application architecture for real-time analytics and aggregation using the name HYRISE.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Former SAP SE executive, Vishal Sikka, mentioned this architecture as "Hasso's New Architecture".
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Before the name "HANA" stabilized, people referred to this product as "New Database".
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The software was previously called "SAP High-Performance Analytic Appliance".
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] A first research paper on HYRISE was published in November 2010.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The research engine is later released open source in 2013, and was reengineered in 2016 to become HYRISE2 in 2017.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The first product shipped in late November 2010.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] By mid-2011, the technology had attracted interest but more experienced business customers considered it to be "in early days".
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] HANA support for SAP NetWeaver Business Warehouse (BW) was announced in September 2011 for availability by November.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] In 2012, SAP promoted aspects of cloud computing.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] In October 2012, SAP announced a platform as a service offering called the SAP HANA Cloud Platform and a variant called SAP HANA One that used a smaller amount of memory.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] In May 2013, a managed private cloud offering called the HANA Enterprise Cloud service was announced.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] In May 2013, Business Suite on HANA became available, enabling customers to run SAP Enterprise Resource Planning functions on the HANA platform.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] S/4HANA, released in 2015, written specifically for the HANA platform, combines functionality for ERP, CRM, SRM and others into a single HANA system.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] S/4HANA is intended to be a simplified business suite, replacing earlier generation ERP systems.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] While it is likely that SAP will focus its innovations on S/4HANA, some customers using non-HANA systems have raised concerns of being locked into SAP products.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Since S/4HANA requires an SAP HANA system to run, customers running SAP business suite applications on hardware not certified by SAP would need to migrate to a SAP-certified HANA database should they choose the features offered by S/4HANA.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Rather than versioning, the software utilizes service packs, referred to as Support Package Stacks (SPS), for updates.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Support Package Stacks are released every 6 months.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] In November 2016 SAP announced SAP HANA 2, which offers enhancements to multiple areas such as database management and application management and includes two new cloud services: Text Analysis and Earth Observation Analysis.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] HANA customers can upgrade to HANA 2 from SPS10 and above.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Customers running SPS9 and below must first upgrade to SPS12 before upgrading to HANA 2 SPS01.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Storing data in main memory rather than on disk provides faster data access and, by extension, faster querying and processing.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is a more costly form of data storage.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Column-oriented systems store all data for a single column in the same location, rather than storing all data for a single row in the same location (row-oriented systems).
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] This can enable performance improvements for OLAP queries on large datasets and allows greater vertical compression of similar types of data in a single column.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] If the read times for column-stored data is fast enough, consolidated views of the data can be performed on the fly, removing the need for maintaining aggregate views and its associated data redundancy.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Although row-oriented systems have traditionally been favored for OLTP, in-memory storage opens techniques to develop hybrid systems suitable for both OLAP and OLTP capabilities, removing the need to maintain separate systems for OLTP and OLAP operations.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The index server performs session management, authorization, transaction management and command processing.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The database has both a row store and a columnar store.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Users can create tables using either store, but the columnar store has more capabilities and is most frequently used.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The index server also manages persistence between cached memory images of database objects, log files and permanent storage files.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The XS engine allows web applications to be built.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] SAP HANA Information Modeling (also known as SAP HANA Data Modeling) is a part of HANA application development.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Modeling is the methodology to expose operational data to the end user.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Reusable virtual objects (named calculation views) are used in the modelling process.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] SAP HANA manages concurrency through the use of multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), which gives every transaction a snapshot of the database at a point in time.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] When an MVCC database needs to update an item of data, it will not overwrite the old data with new data, but will instead mark the old data as obsolete and add the newer version.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] In a scale-out environment, HANA can keep volumes of up to a petabyte of data in memory while returning query results in under a second.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] However, RAM is still much more expensive than disk space, so the scale-out approach is only feasible for certain time critical use cases.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] SAP HANA includes a number of analytic engines for various kinds of data processing.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The Business Function Library includes a number of algorithms made available to address common business data processing algorithms such as asset depreciation, rolling forecast and moving average.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The Predictive Analytics Library includes native algorithms for calculating common statistical measures in areas such as clustering, classification and time series analysis.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] HANA incorporates the open source statistical programming language R as a supported language within stored procedures.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The column-store database offers graph database capabilities.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The graph engine processes the Cypher Query Language and also has a visual graph manipulation via a tool called Graph Viewer.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Graph data structures are stored directly in relational tables in HANA's column store.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Pre-built algorithms in the graph engine include pattern matching, neighborhood search, single shortest path, and strongly connected components.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Typical usage situations for the Graph Engine include examples like supply chain traceability, fraud detection, and logistics and route planning.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] HANA also includes a spatial database engine which implements spatial data types and SQL extensions for CRUD operations on spatial data.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] HANA is certified by the Open Geospatial Consortium, and it integrates with ESRI's ArcGIS geographic information system.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] In addition to numerical and statistical algorithms, HANA can perform text analytics and enterprise text search.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] HANA's search capability is based on “fuzzy” fault-tolerant search, much like modern web-based search engines.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Results include a statistical measure for how relevant search results are, and search criteria can include a threshold of accuracy for results.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Analyses available include identifying entities such as people, dates, places, organizations, requests, problems, and more.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Such entity extraction can be catered to specific use cases such as Voice of the Customer (customer's preferences and expectations), Enterprise (i.e. mergers and acquisitions, products, organizations), and Public Sector (public persons, events, organizations).
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Custom extraction and dictionaries can also be implemented.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Besides the database and data analytics capabilities, SAP HANA is a web-based application server, hosting user-facing applications tightly integrated with the database and analytics engines of HANA.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The "XS Advanced Engine" (XSA) natively works with Node.js and JavaEE languages and runtimes.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] XSA is based on Cloud Foundry architecture and thus supports the notion of “Bring Your Own Language”, allowing developers to develop and deploy applications written in languages and in runtimes other than those XSA implements natively, as well as deploying applications as microservices.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] XSA also allows server-side JavaScript with SAP HANA XS Javascript (XSJS).
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Supporting the application server is a suite of application lifecycle management tools allowing development deployment and monitoring of user-facing applications.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] HANA can be deployed on-premises or in the cloud from a number of cloud service providers.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] HANA can be deployed on-premises as a new appliance from a certified hardware vendor.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Alternatively, existing hardware components such as storage and network can be used as part of the implementation, an approach which SAP calls "Tailored Data Center Integration (TDI)".
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] HANA is certified to run on multiple operating systems including SUSE Linux Enterprise Server and Red Hat Enterprise Linux.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Supported hardware platforms for on-premise deployment include Intel 64 and POWER Systems.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The system is designed to support both horizontal and vertical scaling.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] SAP HANA licensing is primarily divided into two categories.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Used to run SAP applications such as SAP Business Warehouse powered by SAP HANA and SAP S/4HANA.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Used to run both SAP and non-SAP applications.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] This licensing can be used to create custom applications.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] As part of the full use license, features are grouped as editions targeting various use cases.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] In addition, capabilities such as streaming and ETL are licensed as additional options.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] As of March 9, 2017, SAP HANA is available in an **Express Edition**; a streamlined version which can run on laptops and other resource-limited environments.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] The license for SAP HANA, express edition is free of charge, even for productive use up to 32 GB of RAM.
[src:sap-erp/sap-hana] Additional capacity increases can be purchased up to 128 GB of RAM.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP GbR became, in 1981, fully *Systeme, Anwendungen und Produkte in der Datenverarbeitung* (*Systems, Applications and Products in Data Processing*), abbreviated SAP GmbH after a five-year transition period beginning in 1976.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In the late 1980s, it further restructured itself as SAP AG.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Since 7 July 2014, its corporate structure is that of a pan-European *societas Europaea* (SE); as such, its former German corporate identity is now a subsidiary, SAP Deutschland SE & Co.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] KG*.* It has regional offices in 180 countries and 109,973 employees.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP is a component of the DAX and Euro Stoxx 50 stock market indices.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] The company is the largest non-American software company by revenue and the world's fifth-largest publicly traded software company by revenue.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In June 2025, it was the largest European company by market capitalization, as well as one of the 30 most valuable publicly traded companies in the world.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] When Xerox exited the computer hardware manufacturing industry in 1971, it asked IBM to migrate its business systems to IBM technology.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] As part of IBM's compensation for the migration, IBM was given the rights to the Scientific Data Systems (SDS)/SAPE software repository.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Five IBM engineers from the AI department (Dietmar Hopp, Klaus Tschira, Hans-Werner Hector, Hasso Plattner, and Claus Wellenreuther, all from Mannheim, Baden-Württemberg) were working on an enterprise-wide system based on this software, only to be told that it would no longer be necessary.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Rather than abandoning the project, they decided to leave IBM Tech and start another company.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In June 1972 they founded the SAP *Systemanalyse und Programmentwicklung* ("System Analysis and Program Development" / "SAPD") company, as a private partnership under the German Civil Code.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Their first client was the German branch of Imperial Chemical Industries in Östringen, where they developed mainframe programs for payroll and accounting.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Instead of storing the data on punch cards mechanically, as IBM did, they stored it locally in the Electronic System while using a common Logical database for all activities of Organization.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Therefore, they called their software a real-time system, since there was no need to process the punch cards overnight (for this reason their flagship product carried an R in its name until the late 1990s).
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] This first version was also a standalone software that could be offered to other interested parties.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 1973, SAP launched its first commercial product, the RF financial accounting system.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] This system served as the cornerstone in the ongoing development of other software modules of the system that eventually bore the name SAP R/1.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] This offered a common system for multiple tasks.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] This permitted the use of a centralized data storage, improving the maintenance of data.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] From a technical point of view, therefore, a database was necessary.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 1976 SAP GmbH Systeme, Anwendungen und Produkte in der Datenverarbeitung ("Systems, Applications, and Products in Data Processing") was founded as a sales and support subsidiary.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Five years later, the private partnership was dissolved and its rights were passed on to SAP GmbH.The headquarters moved the following year to Walldorf, Germany.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 1979, SAP launched SAP R/2, expanding the capabilities of the system to other areas, such as materials management and production planning.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 1981, SAP brought a re-designed product to market.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] However, SAP R/2 did not improve until between 1985 and 1990.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP developed and released several versions of R/3 through 1995.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In August 1988, SAP GmbH became SAP AG, and public trading started on 4 November 1988.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Shares were listed on the Frankfurt and Stuttgart stock exchanges.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 1995, SAP was included in the German stock index DAX and, on 22 September 2003, SAP was included in the STOXX Europe 50.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In the mid-1990s, SAP transitioned from mainframe computing to a client–server architecture.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 1996 it began its alliance with the Spanish technology consulting firm Seidor, initiating the expansion of SAP solutions throughout Latin America.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 2004, R/3 was replaced with SAP ERP Central Component (ECC) 5.0.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Architectural changes were also made to transition customers to a service-oriented architecture.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] The company's official name became *SAP AG* (a public limited company) after the 2005 annual general meeting.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP ERP 6.0 is the latest version has since been updated through SAP enhancement packs, the most recent being enhancement package 8 for SAP ERP 6.0 in 2016.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Since 2012, SAP has acquired several companies that sell cloud-based products, with several multi-billion-dollar acquisitions seen by analysts as an attempt to challenge competitor Oracle.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 2014 SAP bought Concur Technologies, a provider of cloud-based travel and expense management software, for $8.3 billion, SAP's most expensive purchase to that date.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Analysts' reactions to the purchase were mixed, with Thomas Becker of Commerzbank questioning whether Concur was the right choice for SAP, while Credit Suisse called the acquisition an "aggressive" move.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP also acquired SmartRecruiters in 2025 to replace the recruiting module in its SAP SuccessFactors Human Capital Management suite.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] As part of the acquisition, SmartRecruiter's AI agent assistant, Winston, will interact with SAP's Joule AI products.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] On 21 May 2014, SAP AG announced during the Annual General Meeting of Shareholders that 99% of the shareholder votes approved the conversion of legal form to a European stock corporation (Societas Europaea, SE) and at the same time, elected the first supervisory board of SAP SE.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] The conversion of the company's legal form would take place upon entry in the commercial register, expected to be in July 2014.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] On 7 July 2014, SAP announced it had changed its legal form to a European Company (Societas Europaea, SE).
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] As a result, its German subsidiary was renamed to SAP Deutschland SE & Co.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] The conversion cost the company approximately €4 million.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 2014 IBM and SAP began a partnership to sell cloud-based services.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Likewise, in 2015, SAP also partnered with HPE to provide secure hybrid cloud-based services running the SAP platform.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Both HPE and IBM provide infrastructure services to SAP, and SAP runs its SAP HANA cloud solution on top.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP has announced additional partnerships with Microsoft in order to give customers tools for data visualization, as well as improved mobile applications.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 2015, SAP exceeded its revenue projections due to the expansion in its cloud business and the success of SAP HANA.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] The growth can also be partially attributed to the acquisitions of Concur and Fieldglass.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Since 2017, SAP is a founding member of the EU Cloud Code of Conduct.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Since May 2021 SAP has listed selected Cloud Service adherent to the EU Cloud Code of Conduct as one of the first Cloud Service Providers.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] The company announced plans in 2016 to invest heavily into technology relating to the Internet of things (IoT) as part of a strategy to capitalize on the growth in that market.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] For that purpose, €2 billion is planned for investment in relevant sectors by the end of 2020.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] On 29 January 2019, SAP announced plans to cut approximately 4,000 positions at the company in a strategic plan to shift to more modern cloud-based technologies such as blockchain, quantum computing, machine learning, Internet of Things, and artificial intelligence.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] On 13 April 2021, SAP announced the formation of the joint venture *SAP Fioneer*, a dedicated Financial Services Industry (FSI) Unit between SAP and investment company Dediq GmbH.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Dediq GmbH invested over €500 million in the newly formed unit and received an 80 percent share in return.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP brought its products, organizational units and the sales network into the business and holds 20 percent of the shares.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In June 2025, it was reported that the company had reached €320bn in value and that 4 out of 5 of SAP's client operations were now managed through its cloud business at hyperscale level.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In September 2025, the European Commission opened an investigation into SAP for anti-competitive practices.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Since 1991, SAP has acquired more than 70 companies.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] The SAP Group comprised 226 companies as of December 31, 2024.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP prioritizes organic investments in technologies for long-term product portfolio growth and relevance, while also making targeted acquisitions to complement existing solutions and enhance penetration into key strategic markets.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] As well as its main ERP products, the company also sells database software and technology (particularly its own brand, SAP HANA) and cloud-engineered systems.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP also offers SAP Cloud Infrastructure, its infrastructure-as-a-service (IaaS) cloud platform for running SAP and non-SAP workloads, alongside SAP offerings available on hyperscaler clouds.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP also operates SAP National Security Services (SAP NS2), a U.S.-based subsidiary that delivers SAP solutions for U.S. government and other regulated customers.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] 98 of the 100 largest companies in the world are SAP customers.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Approximately 80% of SAP’s customers are SMEs.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] For the fiscal year 2017 SAP reported earnings of €4 billion, with an annual revenue of €23.5 billion, an increase of 6.3% over the previous fiscal cycle.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP's shares traded at over US$154 per share, and its market capitalization was valued at US$180 billion in December 2023, making it the largest German company by market capitalization.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP uses a two-tier structure of boards with an executive board and a supervisory board.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In October 2019 Jennifer Morgan and Christian Klein were appointed as co-CEOs of SAP.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] The majority of the company's employees are in Germany and United States.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] About 20,000 employees are based in Germany and about 19,311 employees are based in the United States.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] 45 employee representatives were elected in 2022 to the SAP *SE Works Council*, including 15 candidates from the Ver.di and IG Metall trade union lists.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] They represent 17,000 employees of Germany.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Headquarters is responsible for overall management as well as core engineering activities related to product development.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Worldwide customer support is not provided by the field organizations but by a unified organization called Active Global Support (AGS).
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] The company also encourages employees to volunteer through social sabbaticals, sending teams of people to different countries to aid non-profits.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP employees have volunteered in China, India, Brazil, and South Africa.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP Labs Network consists of all major global Research & Development Hubs of SAP, across more than 20 countries and representing more than 80% of SAP’s global engineering workforce.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Major Hubs of SAP are Germany, India, USA and China, and growing Hubs in East Asia, Eastern Europe, Canada and Latin America.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] There are 12 member organizations of the **SAP User Group Executive Network** (SUGEN).
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] The American Users' Group is one of them.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 2016, ASUG acquired The Eventful Group's North American assets.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 2016, ASUG launched the ASUG University program, which is delivered through both hands-on and virtual methods.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Since May 2015, the company has dealt with a series of high-profile bribery investigations, including one that led to them paying $3.9 million to settle U.S.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Securities and Exchange Commission civil charges over a former executive's scheme to bribe Panama government officials in order to win lucrative technology contracts.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In July 2017 allegations were made that SAP had been involved in business transactions with the controversial and politically influential Gupta family in South Africa.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP was accused of paying CAD House, a Gupta-controlled company, R100 million in order to secure a Transnet deal.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP denied the allegations, claiming that the money was paid as "an extension of the sales force", despite CAD House having no prior SAP experience.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] The dealings of the Gupta family with SAP were revealed in a widely publicized e-mail leak.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] As a consequence of the allegations SAP launched an investigation that led to four of its South African managers being placed on administrative leave along with the seizure of their mobile phones and computers.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Claas Kuehnemann was named as acting managing director for Africa while the investigation continued.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] On 26 October 2017 SAP announced that it had voluntarily reported itself to the U.S.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) for a possible violation of US law, including the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA), related to the South African bribery allegations.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] SAP's own investigation, conducted by law firm Baker McKenzie, revealed that SAP had paid $7.7 million in commissions to third-parties linked to the Gupta family while securing contracts worth $48 million with Transnet and Eskom.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 2018 and in an ongoing court battle, Teradata accused SAP of IP theft and fraudulent behaviour.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 2021, in the German weekly news magazine Der Spiegel, additional claims were made of questionable behaviour with regards to SAP's funding of researchers at the University of Mannheim - who were in effect paid by SAP to investigate competitors technology.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In a later article, Der Spiegel magazine maintained that SAP had been neglectful in maintaining strict governance for years.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In June 2022 the German business magazine Manager Magazin published an article stating the management style of the leadership might be responsible for an increased compliance risk.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In February 2019 SAP was accused of 'improper conduct' linked to state contracts in Kenya and Tanzania.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 2021 SAP admitted in a United States court that it exported software to firms in Iran, contrary to US sanctions against Iran, which led to a fine of $8 million.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In May 2022, multiple claims were made of bullying and sexual harassment within the company, with many cases of unwanted advances by senior male managers on female colleagues.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] When complaints were made or information made available, HR were found to be unhelpful or hostile.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] For example, in one case a female employee was groped by a male manager in Sydney while at a company event, but he was never brought to account.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In another case, a female employee was sexually targeted by a manager and asked to keep her web camera on during the day.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] She then complained and was placed under "performance management" - a precursor to being asked to leave the company.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Several female executives, including the Co-CEO left the company, adding to concerns that women were negatively treated, despite SAP then hiring several other senior women from Microsoft.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In 2024 after investigations by the U.S.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Justice Department and the Securities and Exchange Commission, SAP was ordered to pay $220 million to resolve violations of the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act in South Africa, Indonesia, Tanzania, Malawi, Ghana, Kenya, Zimbabwe and Azerbaijan.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] It paid bribes to officials in state-owned enterprises to gain government contracts.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] It entered into a three-year deferred prosecution agreement, paying a criminal penalty of $118.8 million and an administrative forfeiture of $103,396,765.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In South Africa SAP used third-party intermediaries to acquire tenders from various state-owned entities, including Transnet, the South African Revenue Service, the City of Johannesburg, Eskom and the Department of Water and Sanitation.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] In March 2024, SAP agreed to pay R500 million as part of an agreement with South Africa's Special Investigating Unit.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] The agreement indemnifies them against further financial claims related to the bribery, but does not absolve any parties from criminal prosecution.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] On September 3, 2024 it was announced that CTO and Executive Board Member Jürgen Müller reached a mutual agreement to leave the company by the end of the month due to incident of inappropriate behavior at a company event.
[src:sap-erp/sap-se] Following the news of this incident it was reported on September 13, 2024 that German prosecutors have opened a formal investigation of sexual harassment between him and the female employee.
